body:
These aren't equivalent: `&*` cannot be split apart, in general. The first code is equivalent to:

``` rust
fn main(){
    let val = Foo;
    let x: Option<&Foo> = Some(&val);
    let tmp = match x {
        Some(val) => *val,
        None => panic!(),
    };
    let y = &tmp;
}
```

And hence requires creating a "full" `Foo` value on the stack, in `tmp` (i.e. doing a move).

E.g. imagine if it was

``` rust
    let y = &match x {
        Some(val) => *val,
        None => Foo,
    };
```

The code wouldn't know where/when to run the destructor. The true equivalent is changing the first code to:

``` rust
    let y = &*match x {
        Some(val) => val,
        None => panic!(),
    };
```

although this also works:

``` rust
    let y = match x {
        Some(val) => &*val,
        None => panic!(),
    };
```

(In all cases the `&*` is unnecessary, fwiw.)
